rticle_BFam2009115.pdf</meta-value></custom-meta><custom-meta><meta-name>target-type</meta-name><meta-value>OnlinePDF</meta-value></custom-meta><custom-meta><meta-name>pdf-type</meta-name><meta-value>Typeset</meta-value></custom-meta><custom-meta><meta-name>article-type</meta-name><meta-value>BriefCommunication</meta-value></custom-meta><custom-meta><meta-name>journal-subject-primary</meta-name><meta-value>Materials Science</meta-value></custom-meta><custom-meta><meta-name>journal-subject-secondary</meta-name><meta-value>Materials Science, general</meta-value></custom-meta><custom-meta><meta-name>journal-subject-secondary</meta-name><meta-value>Biomaterials</meta-value></custom-meta><custom-meta><meta-name>journal-subject-secondary</meta-name><meta-value>Optical and Electronic Materials</meta-value></custom-meta><custom-meta><meta-name>journal-subject-secondary</meta-name><meta-value>Structural Materials</meta-value></custom-meta><custom-meta><meta-name>journal-subject-secondary</meta-name><meta-value>Energy Systems</meta-value></custom-meta><custom-meta><meta-name>journal-subject-secondary</meta-name><meta-value>Surface and Interface Science, Thin Films</meta-value></custom-meta><custom-meta><meta-name>open-access</meta-name><meta-value>false</meta-value></custom-meta></custom-meta-group></article-meta><notes notes-type="Misc"><p>This research highlight has been approved by the author of the original article and all empirical data contained within has been provided by said author.</p></notes></front><body><p id="Par2">Solar panels could generate a large chunk of the world’s energy needs, but it is vital to improve their efficiency, at low cost. One of the most important components of solar cells are ‘antireflective’ coatings that trap, rather than reflect incident light.</p><p id="Par3">Now, Peichen Yu and co-workers<sup><xref ref-type="bibr" rid="CR1">1</xref></sup> at National Chiao-Tung University in Hsinchu and Academia Sinica in Taipei have developed an antireflective coating with nanometer sized columns of indium tin oxide (ITO). The coating greatly improves the conversion efficiency of solar cells.<fig id="Figa" position="anchor"><caption xml:lang="en"><p>Fig. 1: A surface covered in nano-sized columns of indium tin oxide provides an ‘antireflective’ coating with graded refractive index to capture light and improve the efficiency of solar cells.Copyright © Peichen Yu 2009</p></caption><graphic specific-use="web" mime-subtype="JPEG" xlink:href="MediaObjects/41427_2009_Article_BFam2009115_Figa_HTML.jpg" position="anchor"/></fig></p><p id="Par4">“Nanostructures can be used to manipulate light and hence the optical properties of a material, in a manner similar to quantum structures manipulating electrons,” says Yu. “It was recently demonstrated that the refractive index of a material can be engineered by adjusting the air volume ratio in porous structures.”</p><p id="Par5">Yu and co-workers used electron beam deposition to spray ITO at shallow angles onto gallium arsenide solar cells under a flux of nitrogen gas. They found that instead of forming a porous structure, the ITO were slightly conical columns about 1.2 micrometers in length.</p><p id="Par6">The columns could be described as a ‘crash barrier’ for light, because when the light hits the surface it experiences a gradual, rather than sudden, change in refractive index.</p><p id="Par7">“The major novelty of this work is the type of vapor flux introduced during deposition. We used nitrogen, while others have used oxygen,” says Yu. The nitrogen helped create tin-rich nucleation cores, whose liquid-phase property promoted the absorption of other atoms, which generated rapid growth in one direction to form the nanocolumns.</p><p id="Par8">The nanocolumn surface reduced the reflection of light from the whole visible spectrum, and improved the overall efficiency of the solar cells by 28%. Yu is quick to point out that these optical properties could prove very valuable for other devices. “We have applied the indium tin oxide nanocolumn surfaces on gallium nitride-based light emitting diodes (LEDs). Preliminary results have shown an enhancement in the light output power of 21%, compared to a conventional LED.” The researchers also plan to try other transparent conductive oxides such as nanostructures of aluminum-doped zinc oxide, because of potential shortages of indium.</p></body><back><ref-list id="Bib1"><title>References</title><ref-list><ref id="CR1"><label>1</label><mixed-citation publication-type="journal"><person-group person-group-type="author"><name><surname>Yu</surname><given-names>Peichen</given-names></name><name><surname>Chang</surname><given-names>Chia-Hua</given-names></name><name><surname>Chiu</surname><given-names>Ching-Hua</given-names></name><name><surname>Yang</surname><given-names>Chin-Sheng</given-names></name><name><surname>Yu</surname><given-names>Jue-Chin</given-names></name><name><surname>Kuo</surname><given-names>Hao-Chung</given-names></name><name><surname>Hsu</surname><given-names>Shih-Hsin</given-names></name><name><surname>Chang</surname><given-names>Yia-Chung</given-names></name></person-group><article-title xml:lang="en">Efficiency Enhancement of GaAs Photovoltaics Employing Antireflective Indium Tin Oxide Nanocolumns</article-title><source>Advanced Materials</source><year>2009</year><volume>21</volume><issue>16</issue><fpage>1618</fpage><lpage>1621</lpage><pub-id pub-id-type="other" assigning-authority="ChemPort ( Chemical Abstract Service )">1:CAS:528:DC%2BD1MXltFGitbY%3D</pub-id><pub-id pub-id-type="doi">10.1002/adma.200802563</pub-id></mixed-citation></ref></ref-list></ref-list></back></article></records><facets><facet name="subject"><facet-value count="1">Biomaterials</facet-value><facet-value count="1">Energy Systems</facet-value><facet-value count="1">Materials Science</facet-value><facet-value count="1">Materials Science, general</facet-value><facet-value count="1">Optical and Electronic Materia